Voter Apathy and Non-Participation in the 2024 U.S. General Election

An Exploratory Analysis with Focus on Texas

Annette Strauss Institute for Civic Life, University of Texas at Austin

January 26, 2026

Executive Summary

This exploratory analysis examines voter apathy and non-participation in the 2024 U.S. General Election using two nationally representative surveys: the American National Election Studies (ANES) and the Cooperative Election Study (CES). As researchers at the Annette Strauss Institute for Civic Life based in Texas, we give special attention to Texas-national comparisons and the unique challenges Texas voters face.

Key Findings:

  • The education gap persists: College+ turnout 90.6% vs.<HS 55.8% (gap 34.8 pts)
  • Texas lags behind: Turnout gap vs.nation: CES (validated) 4.9 pts, ANES 9.2 pts, NA pts
  • Over-reporting is common: 26.8% self-report voting while validated as non-voters
  • Political efficacy matters most: High- vs.low-efficacy turnout gap 8.2 pts
  • Young + low-SES Texans face compounded barriers: Non-registration among TX age 18-29, HS 0.0% (n=50)

1 Introduction

1.1 Research Questions

This study examines voter apathy and barriers to political participation in the 2024 U.S. General Election, with focused attention on Texas. We investigate:

  1. Who doesnt register or vote? Demographic and attitudinal patterns of non-participation
  2. Why do people not register? Structural and psychological barriers to registration
  3. Why do registered voters abstain? Predictors of registered, no vote status
  4. How does Texas compare to the nation? State-specific patterns and disparities
  5. Who over-reports voting? Analyzing self-reported vs.validated turnout (social desirability bias)
  6. Intersectionality: How do demographic factors compound to create participation gaps?

1.2 Data Sources

ANES Time Series Cumulative Data File (1948-2024)

  • 2024 Sample: N = 5,521 respondents
  • Texas subsample: N = 209 (unweighted)
  • Mode: Combined sample (web, face-to-face, video, phone)
  • Key feature: Registration and turnout summary variable (VCF0703)
  • Weight: VCF0009z (full combined sample, Type 0 variables for 1970)

CES Cumulative Common Content (2006-2024)

  • 2024 Sample: N = 60,000 respondents
  • Texas subsample: N = 4,816 (unweighted)
  • Mode: Online survey (YouGov panel)
  • Key feature: Validated voter file matching (vv_turnout_gvm, vv_regstatus)
  • Weight: weight (year-specific) or vvweight (validated registered voters only)

1.3 Survey Design Considerations

Weights: - All descriptive statistics use appropriate survey weights - ANES: VCF0009z accounts for multi-mode design and post-stratification - CES: weight for full sample; vvweight when restricting to validated registered voters

Validated Turnout: - CES matches respondents to commercial voter files (L2, Catalist, etc.) - Allows detection of over-reporting (claiming to vote when records show otherwise) - Not all respondents successfully matched; missing values possible

Missing Data: - Listwise deletion for complete-case analysis - Missing values explicitly coded; no imputation - Sample size (N) reported in all tables and figures

Timing of Measures: - ANES: Pre-election attitudes measured before November 2024; post-election turnout after - CES: Pre-wave (October) and post-wave (November-December); validated turnout updated months later

2.2 ANES 2024: Variable Selection and Recoding

# Key variables from ANES codebook:
# VCF0703: Registration & Turnout Summary (1=Not reg, 2=Reg no vote, 3=Voted)
# VCF0901a: State FIPS code
# VCF0901b: State postal abbreviation
# VCF0009z: Full sample weight
# Demographics: VCF0101 (age), VCF0104 (gender), VCF0105a (race), VCF0110 (educ)
# Attitudes: VCF0609, VCF0605, VCF0310, VCF0501, VCF0803

anes_24 <- anes_raw %>%
  filter(VCF0004 == 2024) %>%
  select(
    # ID and geography
    VCF0006, VCF0901a, VCF0901b,
    # Weights
    VCF0009z,
    # Turnout/Registration
    VCF0703, VCF0701, VCF0702,
    # Demographics
    VCF0101, VCF0104, VCF0105a, VCF0105b, VCF0110, VCF0114, VCF0140a, VCF0147,
    # Attitudes
    VCF0301, VCF0609, VCF0605, VCF0310, VCF0803, VCF0450, VCF0501, VCF0311, VCF0613
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    # Geography
    state_fips = VCF0901a,
    state = as_factor(VCF0901b),
    texas = (state_fips == 48),  # Texas FIPS code
    
    # Outcome: Participation
    participation = case_when(
      VCF0703 == 1 ~ "Not registered",
      VCF0703 == 2 ~ "Registered, no vote",
      VCF0703 == 3 ~ "Voted",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    participation = factor(
      participation, 
      levels = c("Voted", "Registered, no vote", "Not registered")
    ),
    
    # Binary: Voted vs. Not
    voted = (VCF0703 == 3),
    registered = (VCF0703 %in% c(2, 3)),
    
    # Demographics
    age = VCF0101,
    age_group = case_when(
      age < 30 ~ "18-29",
      age < 45 ~ "30-44",
      age < 65 ~ "45-64",
      age >= 65 ~ "65+",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    age_group = factor(age_group, levels = c("18-29", "30-44", "45-64", "65+")),
    
    gender = case_when(
      VCF0104 == 1 ~ "Male",
      VCF0104 == 2 ~ "Female",
      VCF0104 == 3 ~ "Other",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    race = case_when(
      VCF0105a == 1 ~ "White",
      VCF0105a == 2 ~ "Black",
      VCF0105a == 3 ~ "Hispanic",
      VCF0105a == 4 ~ "Asian/PI",
      VCF0105a %in% c(5, 6, 7) ~ "Other/Mixed",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    race_simple = case_when(
      VCF0105b == 1 ~ "White",
      VCF0105b == 2 ~ "Black",
      VCF0105b == 3 ~ "Hispanic",
      VCF0105b == 4 ~ "Other",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    educ = case_when(
      VCF0110 == 1 ~ "< High School",
      VCF0110 == 2 ~ "High School",
      VCF0110 == 3 ~ "Some College",
      VCF0110 == 4 ~ "College+",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    educ = factor(educ, levels = c("< High School", "High School", "Some College", "College+")),
    
    educ_detailed = case_when(
      VCF0140a == 1 ~ "< 9th grade",
      VCF0140a == 2 ~ "9-12th, no diploma",
      VCF0140a == 3 ~ "High school graduate",
      VCF0140a == 4 ~ "Some college, no degree",
      VCF0140a == 5 ~ "Associate degree",
      VCF0140a == 6 ~ "Bachelor's degree",
      VCF0140a == 7 ~ "Graduate degree",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    income = VCF0114,
    
    # Attitudes
    # VCF0609: "Government officials don't care what people think"
    # 1=Agree (LOW efficacy), 2=Disagree (HIGH efficacy), 3=Neither
    efficacy_raw = VCF0609,
    efficacy = case_when(
      VCF0609 == 1 ~ "Agree (low efficacy)",
      VCF0609 == 2 ~ "Disagree (high efficacy)",
      VCF0609 == 3 ~ "Neither",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    efficacy = factor(efficacy, levels = c("Agree (low efficacy)", "Neither", "Disagree (high efficacy)")),
    
    # VCF0605: "Federal govt run by few interests (1) or for benefit of all (2)"
    trust_govt_raw = VCF0605,
    trust_govt = case_when(
      VCF0605 == 1 ~ "Few big interests",
      VCF0605 == 2 ~ "Benefit of all",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    trust_govt = factor(trust_govt, levels = c("Few big interests", "Benefit of all")),
    
    # VCF0310: Interest in elections (1=Not much, 2=Somewhat, 3=Very)
    interest_raw = VCF0310,
    interest = case_when(
      VCF0310 == 1 ~ "Not much interested",
      VCF0310 == 2 ~ "Somewhat interested",
      VCF0310 == 3 ~ "Very interested",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    interest = factor(interest, levels = c("Very interested", "Somewhat interested", "Not much interested")),
    
    # VCF0301: Party ID (1=Dem, 3=Ind, 5=Rep)
    pid = case_when(
      VCF0301 %in% 0:2 ~ "Democrat",
      VCF0301 == 3 ~ "Independent",
      VCF0301 %in% 4:6 ~ "Republican",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    pid = factor(pid, levels = c("Democrat", "Independent", "Republican")),
    
    # VCF0803: Ideology (1=Liberal, 7=Conservative)
    ideology_raw = VCF0803,
    ideology = case_when(
      VCF0803 %in% 1:2 ~ "Liberal",
      VCF0803 %in% 3:5 ~ "Moderate",
      VCF0803 %in% 6:7 ~ "Conservative",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    # VCF0501: See important differences between parties? (1=No, 2=Yes)
    see_party_diff = case_when(
      VCF0501 == 1 ~ "No difference",
      VCF0501 == 2 ~ "Yes, important differences",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    # VCF0613: "People like me have say in government"
    # 1=Agree (high efficacy), 2=Disagree (low efficacy), 3=Neither
    have_say_raw = VCF0613,
    have_say = case_when(
      VCF0613 == 1 ~ "Agree (high efficacy)",
      VCF0613 == 2 ~ "Disagree (low efficacy)",
      VCF0613 == 3 ~ "Neither",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    # Weight
    weight = VCF0009z
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(participation))  # Only complete cases on outcome

2.3 CES 2024: Variable Selection and Recoding

# CES variables:
# vv_turnout_gvm: Validated turnout (0=No, 1=Yes)
# voted_turnout_self: Self-reported turnout
# vv_regstatus: Validated registration (1=Active, 2=Inactive, 3=Unregistered, etc.)
# st: State abbreviation
# weight: Survey weight

ces_24 <- ces_raw %>%
  filter(year == 2024) %>%
  select(
    # ID and geography
    case_id, st,
    # Weights
    weight, vvweight,
    # Turnout/Registration
    vv_regstatus, vv_turnout_gvm, voted_turnout_self, intent_turnout_self,
    # Demographics
    age, birthyr, gender, race, educ, faminc, marstat, ownhome, employ,
    # Attitudes
    ideo5, pid3, pid7, approval_pres, newsint, economy_retro
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    # Geography (st can be labelled numeric; convert safely to character)
    state_label = as_factor(st),
    state = as.character(state_label),
    texas = state %in% c("TX", "Texas"),
    
    # Outcome: Participation (using validated where available, self-report as fallback)
    # Priority: validated turnout > self-report
    voted_validated = case_when(
      vv_turnout_gvm == 1 ~ TRUE,
      vv_turnout_gvm == 2 ~ FALSE,
      TRUE ~ NA
    ),
    voted_self = case_when(
      voted_turnout_self %in% c(1) ~ TRUE,
      voted_turnout_self %in% c(0, 2) ~ FALSE,
      TRUE ~ NA
    ),
    
    # Registration status
    reg_status = case_when(
      vv_regstatus == 1 ~ "Active",
      vv_regstatus == 2 ~ "Inactive",
      vv_regstatus == 3 ~ "Unregistered",
      vv_regstatus == 4 ~ "Matched, dropped/purged",
      vv_regstatus == 5 ~ "Unmatched",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    registered_validated = case_when(
      vv_regstatus %in% c(1, 2) ~ TRUE,
      vv_regstatus == 3 ~ FALSE,
      TRUE ~ NA
    ),
    weight_full = weight,
    weight_validated = if_else(!is.na(vvweight), vvweight, weight),
    
    # Combined participation measure
    participation = case_when(
      # Use validated if available
      !is.na(voted_validated) & voted_validated ~ "Voted",
      !is.na(voted_validated) & !voted_validated & registered_validated ~ "Registered, no vote",
      !is.na(voted_validated) & registered_validated == FALSE ~ "Not registered",
      # Fallback to self-report
      is.na(voted_validated) & voted_self == TRUE ~ "Voted",
      is.na(voted_validated) & voted_self == FALSE ~ "Registered, no vote",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    participation = factor(
      participation, 
      levels = c("Voted", "Registered, no vote", "Not registered")
    ),
    
    # Over-reporting detection (key for lying analysis)
    has_validated = !is.na(voted_validated) & !is.na(voted_self),
    over_reports = (voted_self == TRUE & voted_validated == FALSE),
    under_reports = (voted_self == FALSE & voted_validated == TRUE),
    accurate_report = (voted_self == voted_validated),
    
    # Demographics
    age_group = case_when(
      age < 30 ~ "18-29",
      age < 45 ~ "30-44",
      age < 65 ~ "45-64",
      age >= 65 ~ "65+",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    age_group = factor(age_group, levels = c("18-29", "30-44", "45-64", "65+")),
    generation = case_when(
      birthyr >= 1997 ~ "Gen Z",
      birthyr >= 1981 ~ "Millennial",
      birthyr >= 1965 ~ "Gen X",
      birthyr >= 1946 ~ "Boomer",
      birthyr < 1946 ~ "Silent/Greatest",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    generation = factor(generation, levels = c("Gen Z", "Millennial", "Gen X", "Boomer", "Silent/Greatest")),
    
    gender_cat = as_factor(gender),
    race_cat = as_factor(race),
    educ_cat = as_factor(educ),
    income_cat = case_when(
      faminc < 7 ~ "Under $50k",
      faminc >= 7 & faminc < 11 ~ "$50k-$100k",
      faminc >= 11 ~ "Over $100k",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    income_cat = factor(income_cat, levels = c("Under $50k", "$50k-$100k", "Over $100k")),
    
    # Attitudes
    ideology = case_when(
      ideo5 == 1 ~ "Liberal",
      ideo5 == 2 ~ "Liberal",
      ideo5 == 3 ~ "Moderate",
      ideo5 == 4 ~ "Conservative",
      ideo5 == 5 ~ "Conservative",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    pid = as_factor(pid3),
    
    news_interest = case_when(
      newsint == 1 ~ "Most of the time",
      newsint == 2 ~ "Some of the time",
      newsint == 3 ~ "Only now and then",
      newsint == 4 ~ "Hardly at all",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    ),
    
    econ_retro = as_factor(economy_retro)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(participation))

3.2 Participation by Demographics (National)

# Function to create demographic crosstabs with sample sizes
demo_crosstab_anes <- function(var, var_name) {
  anes_24 %>%
    filter(!is.na(!!sym(var))) %>%
    group_by(!!sym(var), participation) %>%
    summarise(
      n = n(),
      n_weighted = sum(weight, na.rm = TRUE),
      .groups = "drop"
    ) %>%
    group_by(!!sym(var)) %>%
    mutate(
      pct = n_weighted / sum(n_weighted) * 100,
      total_n = sum(n)
    ) %>%
    select(!!sym(var), participation, n, pct, total_n) %>%
    pivot_wider(
      names_from = participation,
      values_from = c(pct, n),
      values_fill = list(pct = 0, n = 0)
    ) %>%
    mutate(Variable = var_name, .before = 1) %>%
    rename(Group = !!sym(var))
}

# Education
tab_educ <- demo_crosstab_anes("educ", "Education")

# Race
tab_race <- demo_crosstab_anes("race", "Race/Ethnicity")

# Age group
tab_age <- demo_crosstab_anes("age_group", "Age Group")

# Gender
tab_gender <- demo_crosstab_anes("gender", "Gender")

# Combine and display
bind_rows(tab_educ, tab_race, tab_age, tab_gender) %>%
  select(Variable, Group, total_n, 
         `pct_Voted`, `pct_Registered, no vote`, `pct_Not registered`) %>%
  nice_table(title = "Table 2. Participation by Demographics (ANES 2024, National, Weighted %)")

4 Attitudinal Predictors of Non-Participation

Beyond demographics, we examine how political attitudes shape participation decisions.

4.1 Political Efficacy: Do Officials NOT Care?

Question phrasing: Government officials dont care what people like me think. (ANES VCF0609)
Interpretation: Agreeing = low efficacy; Disagreeing = high efficacy

# ANES: Efficacy and voting
anes_24 %>%

4.6 Personal Efficacy: People Like Me Have a Say

Distinction from Political Efficacy: - Political efficacy (VCF0609): Do government officials care about people like me? measures whether respondents believe officials are responsive. - Personal efficacy (VCF0613): People like me have a say in government measures whether respondents believe they have personal agency to influence outcomes.

Response options: 1=Agree (high personal efficacy), 2=Disagree (low personal efficacy), 3=Neither

anes_24 %>%

8 Technical Appendix

8.1 Survey Weights

ANES (VCF0009z): - Post-stratified to match U.S. population demographics (age, gender, race, education) - Accounts for multi-mode sample design (web, FTF, video, phone) - For Type 0 variables in 1970 (most variables in this analysis)

CES (weight, vvweight): - weight: Year-specific, post-stratified to Current Population Survey benchmarks - vvweight: Weights to validated registered voter population (use when analyzing turnout among registrants) - We use weight for full-sample analyses, vvweight when restricting to validated voters

8.2 Missing Data

  • Listwise deletion for incomplete cases on outcome variable
  • Missing values on predictors retained when possible (e.g., attitudes)
  • CES validated turnout missing for ~5% of sample (not matched to voter file)

8.3 Sample Sizes and Power

  • ANES Texas subsample: N = 209 (sufficient for state-level estimates but underpowered for 3-way crosstabs)
  • CES Texas subsample: N = 4,816 (robust for detailed breakdowns)
  • Minimum cell size: Tables suppress cells with N < 30 to avoid unstable estimates

8.4 Validated Turnout Methodology (CES)

  • CES matches respondents to commercial voter files (L2 Political, Catalist)
  • Match rate: ~95% of respondents successfully matched
  • Turnout coded as 1 if voter file shows participation in November 2024 general election
  • Limitation: Voter files may have errors (e.g., same-name matches, address changes)

8.5 Codebook References

All variables coded per official codebooks: - ANES: ANES Time Series Cumulative Data File Variable Codebook (December 11, 2025) - CES: Guide to the Cumulative Common Content of the Cooperative Election Study (Shiro Kuriwaki, 2025-10-08)

Full codebooks available in raw_data/ directory.
